summary: Clearly, heaven came up with lemon and Crowley, for hell, responsed with "let's ruin this gift from god by making another yellow...
body:
Clearly, heaven came up with lemon and Crowley, for hell, responsed with “let’s ruin this gift from god by making another yellow flavour that literally embodies disappointment and disgust. What flavor? Banana, of course. That way humans have to play Russian roulette with any yellow candy”

The same later happened when heaven made cherry flavoring. All of the sudden, strawberry existed too. Yes I know Aziraphale ordered a strawberry popsicle but he could have been keeping up appearances or supporting his husband’s creations don’t @ me

summary: Crawly remembers the day he was shut out of heaven.  The last day he spent as an angel, walking along the golden streets, warm...
body:
Crawly remembers the day he was shut out of heaven.  The last day he spent as an angel, walking along the golden streets, warm wind tousling his long hair, pearl white wings fluttering in the breeze.  He remembers when he last saw Her face, clouded and heartbroken as She gave Her final judgment.  He remembers watching it all slowly fade away as his wings blackened, as his eyes grew yellow and slitted, as he tumbled towards Hell with the rest of the fallen.

He always thought he’d never see it again, would never catch a glimpse of Heaven after his fall.  After all, he’s a demon now; his home is Hell and filth and burning fire.  Never again would he see his home.

Now he stood on the walls of Eden, his black wings folded, yellow eyes staring at the angel beside him, who’d given his miraculous flaming sword away because someone else needed it more than him.

And for the first time in a very long time, Crawly sees heaven again.

summary: So I was rewatching Good Omens last night and something occurred to me. We all know the “You go too fast for me, Crowley” when...
body:
So I was rewatching Good Omens last night and something occurred to me. We all know the “You go too fast for me, Crowley” when the demon offers his crush Aziraphale a lift, a scene I’m calling Scene 1.

And because that’s in Ep.3, it’s easy enough for us to refer that back to this delightful scene (Scene 2) in Ep.2 on the way to Tadfield (watch the road, watCH THE ROAD!!!)

But chronologically? No. Scene 1 is 1967, while the second one is present day. It’s not a reference to Scene 2 because this scene hasn’t happened yet. Now, given that the scene immediately prior to this ends with Crowley offering Aziraphale a lift out of the bombed church (i mean it ends with Az falling hopelessly in love but anyway), it’s possible that Az is familiar with how Crowley drives, all I’m saying is that there is definite weight to the argument that what he really means is “I’m sorry, I’m just not ready for that yet”
